ODCP Lessons Learned - Response requested,"To all current and former team members of the ODCP Benefits Correction Project,

We are currently winding down the project, which is scheduled to conclude in March.  At ODCP request, we are preparing a presentation of Lessons Learned throughout the benefit correction process, and we would appreciate your feedback.

We are looking for any insight you may have into what went well, and what did not, throughout all parts of the benefit correction process, including T01 (recalculation), T03 (initial communication and call center set up), and D01 (due process).  We are NOT looking for any feedback on TO2 and TO4 (quality assurance).  I know some of you have been off the team for quite some time, however any thoughts/ideas/memories/nightmares that you can recall would assist us immensely.
Some general themes to consider would be:
These are just a few examples; please feel free to comment on these or anything else you can think of.

We would like feedback as soon as possible, with a response ideally by Wednesday, the 23rd.  Please let me know if you dont think youll be able to respond by then.  Also, if anyone wants to catch up and discuss in person, my schedule is fairly open this week J.

Thanks to everyone for all the hard work on this engagement.  I did not get the chance to work with all of you, but the effort that went into all phases of this project have been a great help on my first Deloitte staffing!
Please consider the environment before printing.

column2: From my perspective, and based on the conversation with Carl, I would suggest focusing on the following FEVS items to construct the Bullying Resilience index. These are proximal measures at  the best of an anti-bullying workplace culture, but the since the FEVS is a standard survey there are not many items that address bullying, workplace violence, coercion, or hostile working environment in any direct way.

column1: (36) My organization has prepared employees for potential security threats.
(34) Policies and programs promote diversity in the workplace (for example, recruiting minorities and women, training in awareness of diversity issues, mentoring).
(37) Arbitrary action, personal favoritism and coercion for partisan political purposes are not tolerated.
(49) My supervisor treats me with respect.
(17) I can disclose a suspected violation of any law, rule or regulation without fear of reprisal.
(20) The people I work with cooperate to get the job done.

On Nov 9, 2016, at 8:41 PM, Sanwardeker, Roopa (US - Arlington) <rsanwardeker@deloitte.com <mailto:rsanwardeker@deloitte.com> > wrote:

column3: Team  Given the tight timeline and the interconnectivity with the TOs, I wanted to confirm the sausage making that will go into creating Carl Bennetts anti-bullying index over the next few days.
TO2s activities should roughly align to the schedule below. We will work in close conjunction with Mike and the SRC, as well as TO3.
Do some research around anti-bullying (e.g. articles, other agency activities, etc.)
Identify potential FEVs questions that may relate
Examine existing tools and analysis (e.g. inclusion index, etc.)
Conduct data analysis based on any data that comes in from USAID
Make a client ready presentation (slides maybe? Tableau maybe?)
Please let us know if you would prefer a different approach or this is duplicative with work already being done.
Please consider the environment before printing.

Cc: Bennett, Carl (US - Arlington) <carbennett@deloitte.com <mailto:carbennett@deloitte.com> >; Demeke, Maria (US - Arlington) <mdemeke@deloitte.com <mailto:mdemeke@deloitte.com> >; Reilly, Kate (US - Arlington) <kreilly@deloitte.com <mailto:kreilly@deloitte.com> >; Carr, Wendy (US - Arlington) <wcarr@deloitte.com <mailto:wcarr@deloitte.com> >; Donahey, Mark (US - Arlington) <mdonahey@deloitte.com <mailto:mdonahey@deloitte.com> >
We really enjoyed the discussion today. As a follow up to our conversation around anti-bullying, I wanted to summarize our understanding and next steps.

HCTM has been making progress around anti-bullying efforts at the agency. There have been plans to deploy a survey to understand the impact of bullying at the agency. To assist, Deloitte will examine USAID FEVS data to create an anti-bullying index and supplement the analysis with additional data points.
FEVS full FY16 dataset including de-identified individual responses with demographic data where possible (occupation, office/division, etc.)
Any qualitative information around the anti-bullying efforts (optional)
HCTM to send Deloitte FEVS and other data no later than COB tomorrow, 11/10
Deloitte to provide initial analysis to USAID no later than noon on Tuesday, 11/15
HCTM to provide feedback by noon on Wednesday, 11/16
Deloitte to revise analysis and support HCTM on Thursday, 11/17
Happy to answer any questions. Looking forward to getting started on this analysis!
Please consider the environment before printing.

eRoom alert: Notice of Benefit Change - James Trainor,"Hi Kande,
Below is a link to the benefit adjustment letter for James Trainor.  The calculation file is in the same folder.  Please let us know if you have any questions.
Please check out this item in the ODCP Task Order 03 Calculations (P-Z) eRoom:
ODCP Task Order 03 Calculations (P-Z)/ Trainor, James
To turn on notification for this item, go to:

To: Brownlee, Sean (US - Arlington) <sbrownlee@deloitte.com>; Ostroff, Adrienne (US - Arlington) <adostroff@deloitte.com>; Gannaway, Alexis (US - Arlington) <agannaway@deloitte.com>; Goldstein, Marlee (US - Arlington) <margoldstein@deloitte.com>; Bicks, Emily (US - Arlington) <embicks@deloitte.com>

When I was reviewing James Trainors case for a fault determination, a question arose regarding his prior government service that he purchased.  The original benefit calculation gave him credit for 9 months and 8 days of purchased service; the 3/1/2015 recalculation corrected this to 8 months and 29 days.  However, upon further review, an additional adjustment is needed.

His prior government service was with the Executive Protective Service (EPS).  This service should have been credited as departmental service, not as purchased service.  This will result in a net underpayment (error in his average pay resulted in an overpayment) and will eliminate his debt.
*         At the time he was appointed to MPD, the plan defined police or fire service to include service with the White House Police force. [Pub. L. 85-157]
*         Executive Protective Service was substituted for White House Police force wherever referenced. [Pub. L. 91-297]

Please recalculate his benefit assuming the correction is made beginning with the 12/1/2015 benefit payment.  Assume the letter will state that his service with EPS should have been considered departmental service instead of purchased service.  Not sure yet if well include citations to support and, if so, which citations (Im still working through the basis with OGC).
Cc: Nancy.Ostrowski@treasury.gov; Gilmartin, Michael M (US - Atlanta) <mgilmartin@deloitte.com>; Gannaway, Alexis (US - Arlington) <agannaway@deloitte.com>
Subject: RE: Age-of-Error Standard Call Scripts
Looks good  just a few tweaks.
You might want to take a look at the notice on the retired firefighters website to see if you need to add to your scripts.  I dont think you will, but you may have a different take.
Cc: Ostrowski, Nancy; Gilmartin, Michael M (US - Atlanta); Gannaway, Alexis (US - Arlington)

Attached are a list of questions we anticipate receiving with regards to the AES communications that are going out.  We used the draft communications you provided as a basis for what callers may know coming in, and what we should or should not share.  Please let us know if you have any changes, or if you would like to discuss.
Please consider the environment before printing.

RE: Introduction,"Hi Emily  Im actually sitting on 13 today. Come find me outside 13174. Im at the table for 4 against the windows facing Georgetown, underneath the sign that says Human Capital.

If You Haven't Already:  ACTION REQUIRED by Saturday 11:59pm CT,"
Deloitte Consulting LLP |  For internal use only
Take Action (if you havent already): Log into STAFFIT to confirm your schedule

As a reminder, all Deloitte professionals are responsible for keeping their schedule current and confirming it in STAFFIT <https://rmss.deloitteresources.com/irj/portal>  each week by Saturday 11:59pm CT. You can also review and confirm your schedule by downloading <https://deloittenet.deloitte.com/WT/Tech/Software/Pages/MobileAppsMain.aspx>  the STAFFIT mobile app.  Professionals can modify their schedule throughout the week, but are expected to check the confirmation box in STAFFIT each week between Sunday and Saturday.
Each week, please review your schedule for accuracy and completeness by doing the following:
Verify and update all future client service assignments on your STAFFIT schedule
Verify and update all future time allocations* (PTO, training, conferences, etc.) on your STAFFIT schedule

Manually remove assignment hours from the days that also have time allocations and holidays <https://deloittenet.deloitte.com/news/publishing/1115/pages/1118152016holidays.aspx>  (Memorial Day, Independence Day, Labor Day, Impact Day, etc.). STAFFIT does not automatically adjust assignment hours when time allocations* (PTO, training, conferences, etc.) are added.

o   For more information on how to enter time allocations and update client assignments please use the Enter Time Allocations and Update Assignments job-aid <https://deloittenet.deloitte.com/PC/PracticeComm/functions/Consulting/Career/Documents/EnterTimeandUpdateAssignments.pdf>
o   Please note, only resource managers have the ability to modify historical data in STAFFIT.  If you require edits to historical data, please work with your resource manager.

Check STAFFIT Corner <https://deloittenet.deloitte.com/pc/practicecomm/functions/consulting/career/pages/staffit.aspx>  for FAQs, job-aids, training, and more information on STAFFIT. For technical assistance, dial 2222 from an office phone or 1-800-DELOITTE.
